1. Overview
This runbook covers all steps required after replication is established — from pre-cutover preparation through final cutover execution, VM validation on NC2, post-migration health checks, application-level testing, and source VM decommissioning.

This document assumes the following from Part 1 are complete:
•	Nutanix Move appliance is deployed and healthy on vCenter
•	vCenter source and NC2 AHV target are configured in Move
•	All in-scope VMs are in 'Replicating' status with delta syncs completing successfully
•	Test cutover has been performed and validated on at least one VM

1.1 Migration Phases Covered in This Runbook
Phase	Description	Key Actions
Phase 1	Pre-Cutover Preparation	Communication, delta sync validation, rollback plan, team readiness
Phase 2	Final Cutover Execution	Quiesce source VMs, trigger final cutover in Move, IP/MAC update
Phase 3	Post-Cutover VM Validation	Boot validation, NIC, OS, services, application smoke tests
Phase 4	Post-Migration Health Checks	Infrastructure, storage, network, monitoring integration
Phase 5	Source VM Decommissioning	Retain source VMs in powered-off state, then decommission after hold period
Phase 6	Stakeholder Sign-off	Application owner, infrastructure, and change board sign-off

 
2. Pre-Cutover Preparation

📋  Timing:  Pre-cutover preparation should be completed at least 24–48 hours before the migration window. Steps in this section do not impact production VMs.

2.1 Communication & Stakeholder Readiness

STEP
1	Send Pre-Migration Communication to Stakeholders
	1. Send migration notification to all relevant stakeholders at least 48 hours in advance:
   • Application owners and end users (expected downtime window)
   • IT operations / helpdesk (to manage any incident calls during window)
   • Management / change board (final approval confirmation)
   • Network / security teams (on standby during cutover)

2. Communication should include:
   • Migration window start and end time (with timezone)
   • List of VMs / applications being migrated
   • Expected downtime per application
   • Rollback trigger criteria and rollback timeline
   • Contact details for migration lead and escalation chain

3. Confirm change window is approved in the Change Management system (ServiceNow / JIRA / etc.).

4. Obtain written/email confirmation from application owners that pre-migration backups are complete.

2.2 Final Replication Health Check

STEP
2	Validate Replication Status Before Cutover Window
	1. Log in to Nutanix Move UI (https://<Move-IP>:8443).
2. For each VM in scope, verify:
   ✓ Status:          'Replicating' (not paused, errored, or stopped)
   ✓ Last Delta Sync: Completed within the last 1–2 hours
   ✓ Data Lag:        < 5 GB (or within acceptable RPO threshold)
   ✓ Errors:          Zero active errors in Move event log

3. In Prism Element (NC2), verify replicated VM disk files exist in the target container.
4. Confirm no active snapshots are stuck on source VMs in vCenter.
5. If any VM shows 'Error' status in Move — resolve the issue before proceeding with cutover.
   Do NOT cutover VMs with pending replication errors.

6. Trigger a manual delta sync for all VMs immediately before the cutover window:
   Move UI → Migration Plan → Actions → Sync Now
7. Wait for manual sync to complete (status: 'Sync Complete') before proceeding.

2.3 Pre-Cutover VM Preparation

STEP
3	Prepare Source VMs for Cutover
	1. BACKUP VERIFICATION:
   Confirm that a full VM backup (via Veeam, Commvault, VADP, or snapshot) exists for all
   in-scope VMs taken within the last 24 hours. Record backup job IDs / timestamps.

2. APPLICATION QUIESCING PREP:
   Work with application owners to identify any pre-shutdown steps required:
   • Database VMs: flush transactions, run checkpoint, put in maintenance mode
   • Web application VMs: drain active sessions, disable load balancer member
   • Active Directory / DNS VMs: ensure other DCs are available before shutdown
   • Clustered services: gracefully fail over clustered roles to non-migrating nodes

3. AGENT CONFIRMATION (if using agent-based mode):
   Verify Move Agent is connected on all target VMs in Move UI (green status).
   Run a final agent-triggered sync: Move UI → VM → Force Sync.

4. DNS / IPAM READINESS:
   Pre-stage DNS record updates (if IP addresses will change post-migration).
   Confirm DHCP/IPAM scopes are ready on the NC2 network for migrated VMs.
   If retaining IPs — confirm no IP conflicts exist on the target NC2 subnet.

5. MONITORING SUPPRESSION:
   Suppress/silence monitoring alerts for the VMs being migrated in the monitoring tool
   (e.g., Nagios, Zabbix, Prometheus, Datadog, Nutanix Prism Alerts) for the migration window.
   This prevents alert storms during the planned downtime.

2.4 Rollback Plan

STEP
4	Document and Confirm Rollback Procedure
	Rollback Criteria — initiate rollback if ANY of the following occur:
  • Migrated VM fails to power on NC2 after 3 attempts
  • Application fails smoke test on NC2 and cannot be resolved within the RTO window
  • Network connectivity cannot be established on NC2 target VM
  • Data integrity issue detected (disk size mismatch, corrupted OS)

Rollback Procedure:
  1. In Move UI: Stop cutover for the affected VM (if final cutover in progress).
  2. Power off the partially-migrated VM on NC2 (if it was powered on).
  3. Power ON the source VM on vCenter — it was kept powered off, not deleted.
     (Move does NOT delete source VMs automatically.)
  4. Re-enable monitoring alerts for the source VM.
  5. Notify stakeholders of rollback — restore normal operations on vCenter.
  6. Investigate root cause in Move logs before re-attempting migration.

Rollback Time Estimate:  5–10 minutes per VM (power on source VM)
Rollback Decision Authority: Migration Lead + Application Owner
Maximum time before rollback decision: As per agreed RTO (recommended: 30–60 mins per VM)


 
3. Final Cutover Execution

🔴  DOWNTIME BEGINS:  Source VMs will be powered off during final cutover. Ensure all pre-cutover steps are complete and the maintenance window is active before proceeding.

STEP
5	Quiesce and Shut Down Source VM on vCenter
	Execute for each VM — follow the order: Database VMs → App VMs → Web VMs.

1. If applicable, perform application-level shutdown first:
   Database: Run SHUTDOWN IMMEDIATE (Oracle) or STOP SERVICE (MSSQL)
   Web/App: Stop application services gracefully via service manager / startup scripts

2. Log in to the source VM via RDP/SSH and perform a clean OS shutdown:
   Windows:  Start → Shut Down (or: shutdown /s /t 0)
   Linux:    sudo shutdown -h now

3. Confirm the VM shows 'Powered Off' in vCenter Web Client.
   Do NOT force-power off unless the OS does not respond after 5 minutes.

4. Record the exact power-off time for each VM (for RPO calculation and audit).

5. Do NOT remove snapshots or delete VM from vCenter at this stage.


STEP
6	Trigger Final Cutover in Nutanix Move
	1. Log in to Move UI (https://<Move-IP>:8443).
2. Navigate to the Migration Plan → select the VM(s) to cut over.
3. Click 'Cutover' (or 'Finalize Migration') for each VM.
   Move will perform the following automatically:
   a) Take a final snapshot of the source VM (powered-off state — crash-consistent).
   b) Replicate any remaining changed blocks to NC2 (final delta sync).
   c) Convert the VM disk format to AHV-compatible format (qcow2).
   d) Inject Nutanix VirtIO drivers (storage and NIC drivers for AHV).
   e) Update VM boot configuration for AHV (remove VMware tools / VMX references).
   f) Register the VM on Prism Element (NC2) with the configured vCPU, RAM, network.

4. Monitor the cutover progress in Move UI — typical duration: 5–30 minutes per VM
   (depends on remaining delta size and network throughput).

5. When Move shows status: 'Cutover Complete' for the VM, proceed to next step.

6. DO NOT power on the target VM in Prism yet — complete the IP/network step first.


STEP
7	Update Network Configuration on Target VM (NC2)
	1. In Prism Element (NC2), navigate to: VM → locate the migrated VM.
2. Verify the VM's network adapter is mapped to the correct target network/VLAN.
   If incorrect: VM → Update → Network Adapters → change to the correct network.

3. IP ADDRESS STRATEGY — choose one:

   OPTION A — Retain Source IP (same subnet / stretched L2):
   • Ensure the source VM is powered off (to avoid IP conflict).
   • The migrated VM will request the same IP via DHCP (if DHCP-configured) or via static config.
   • Verify DHCP reservation exists for the MAC address of the NC2 VM.
   • Note: The MAC address WILL change after migration — update DHCP reservation if needed.
     Get new MAC: Prism → VM → Details → Network → MAC Address.

   OPTION B — Assign New IP (different subnet):
   • Note the new IP to be assigned.
   • After VM powers on (Step 8), log in and update the guest OS IP configuration:
     Windows: Network Adapter Settings → set static IP / update DHCP scope
     Linux:   Edit /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-ethX or /etc/netplan/*.yaml

4. If DNS records need updating — prepare DNS change (do not apply yet; apply after VM is validated online).


 
4. Post-Cutover VM Validation

📋  Goal:  Verify the migrated VM is fully functional on NC2 before declaring the migration successful. Perform all checks before enabling production traffic.

4.1 VM Boot and OS Validation

STEP
8	Power On and Validate VM Boot on NC2 (AHV)
	1. In Prism Element, select the migrated VM → click 'Power On'.
2. Open the VM Console: VM → Launch Console (VNC).
3. Monitor the boot sequence:
   ✓ BIOS/UEFI POST completes
   ✓ Bootloader (GRUB / Windows Boot Manager) loads
   ✓ OS kernel initialises without errors
   ✓ OS reaches login prompt / desktop / runlevel

4. WINDOWS SPECIFIC BOOT CHECKS:
   • Confirm no BSOD (Blue Screen of Death) — most common cause: VirtIO driver issues.
   • If BSOD occurs with INACCESSIBLE_BOOT_DEVICE: Move VirtIO driver injection may have failed.
     Resolution: Boot from WinPE → inject VirtIO drivers manually → reboot.
   • Confirm Windows reaches the login screen within 5 minutes.
   • Log in and verify Windows Event Log: No critical boot errors in System log.

5. LINUX SPECIFIC BOOT CHECKS:
   • Confirm kernel boots without kernel panic.
   • Verify dracut/initrd contains VirtIO modules: lsmod | grep virtio
   • Confirm systemd services start cleanly: systemctl list-units --failed
   • If VM boots to emergency mode: check /etc/fstab — update any stale disk UUID references.
     Use: blkid to get new UUIDs on AHV, update /etc/fstab accordingly.

6. Confirm VM hostname is correct: hostname -f (Linux) / hostname (Windows CMD)

4.2 Network Connectivity Validation

STEP
9	Validate Network Connectivity on Migrated VM
	1. Within the VM console, verify the NIC is detected and has an IP assigned:
   Windows:  ipconfig /all
   Linux:    ip addr show  OR  ifconfig -a

2. Verify the correct IP, subnet mask, and gateway are configured.

3. Test gateway connectivity (confirm VM can reach its default gateway):
   ping <default-gateway-IP>

4. Test DNS resolution:
   Windows:  nslookup <internal-hostname>
   Linux:    dig <internal-hostname> OR nslookup <internal-hostname>

5. Test connectivity to key internal resources:
   ping <AD Domain Controller IP>
   ping <DNS Server IP>
   ping <Application dependency IPs>

6. If IP changed — apply the DNS record update now:
   Update the A/PTR record for the VM in your DNS management tool.
   Verify DNS propagation: nslookup <vm-hostname> from another machine.

7. Test RDP/SSH access from the network (not just console):
   From an external machine: ssh <user>@<new-VM-IP> OR mstsc to <new-VM-IP>
   Confirm remote access is working before proceeding.

8. If the VM is domain-joined (Windows AD):
   Verify domain membership: System Properties → Computer Name → Domain
   Test: nltest /sc_verify:<domain-name>
   If domain trust broken: Disjoin and rejoin the domain, or use netdom reset.

4.3 Storage and Disk Validation

STEP
10	Validate Disk and Storage Configuration
	1. Confirm all disks/volumes are online and accessible:
   Windows:  Disk Management (diskmgmt.msc) → all volumes show 'Healthy'
   Linux:    lsblk -f  AND  df -h  (all mount points accessible, correct sizes)

2. Verify disk sizes match the source:
   Windows:  Get-Disk | Select Number,Size,FriendlyName  (PowerShell)
   Linux:    lsblk

3. Confirm all mount points / drive letters are correct.
   Linux: Cat /etc/fstab — verify entries; mount -a to test
   Windows: Check drive letters in Disk Management

4. Run a basic read/write test on each volume:
   Linux: dd if=/dev/zero of=/tmp/testfile bs=1M count=512; rm /tmp/testfile
   Windows: Write a test file to each drive and delete it

5. Verify no snapshot artifacts or .vmdk references are present.
   On the NC2 VM, there should be clean qcow2 or AHV-format disks only.

6. Check filesystem consistency (optional but recommended):
   Linux: sudo e2fsck -n /dev/sdX  (non-destructive check)
   Windows: chkdsk C: (check only — /f flag only if issues found)

4.4 Application and Services Validation

STEP
11	Validate Application Services and Smoke Test
	1. Verify critical OS services are running:
   Windows:  services.msc — check all required services are in 'Running' state
   Linux:    systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running

2. Check for any failed services:
   Linux: systemctl --failed
   Windows: Event Viewer → Windows Logs → System → filter for Error/Critical

3. Start application-specific services (if they were stopped before cutover):
   Database: Start DB service and verify it initialises correctly
   Web/App:  Start web server / application server services
   Middleware: Start queue brokers, caches, etc.

4. SMOKE TESTS — work with application owner to run:
   • Web application: Load the application URL — verify homepage loads, login works
   • Database: Connect to DB, run a test query, verify row counts match pre-migration snapshot
   • API service: Run a sample API call, verify expected response
   • File shares / NFS: Access shares, read/write a test file
   • Windows AD / LDAP: Test LDAP bind and user authentication

5. Check application log files for errors post-startup:
   Look in: /var/log/<app>/, C:\<AppName>\logs\

6. Verify scheduled tasks / cron jobs are present and configured:
   Linux:    crontab -l  AND  ls /etc/cron.d/
   Windows:  Task Scheduler → verify tasks exist and next run times are correct

7. Record the application smoke test results — pass/fail per test case.


 
5. Post-Migration Infrastructure Health Checks
5.1 Nutanix NC2 Cluster Health

STEP
12	Validate NC2 Cluster Health Post-Migration
	1. Log in to Prism Element (https://<NC2-Prism-IP>:9440).
2. Navigate to Home → Health → verify all health checks pass (green).
3. Confirm cluster-wide metrics are within normal range:
   • CPU Utilization:     < 80% across all nodes
   • Memory Utilization:  < 85% across all nodes
   • Storage Usage:       < 75% of usable capacity
   • I/O Latency:         < 2ms average (storage)

4. Verify no degraded CVMs (Controller VMs) or nodes:
   Prism → Hardware → Diagram → all nodes should be blue/healthy
   SSH to any CVM: ncc health_checks run_all  (Nutanix health check CLI)

5. Confirm the migrated VMs' storage container has free space:
   Storage → Storage Containers → check 'Free Space' column.

6. Review Prism Alerts: Prism → Alerts → verify no critical alerts.

7. Verify Nutanix CVM services are all UP:
   SSH to any CVM: genesis status  (all services should show 'UP')

5.2 VM-Level Performance Baseline

STEP
13	Establish Performance Baseline on NC2 VMs
	1. In Prism, navigate to: VM → select migrated VM → Performance tab.
2. Monitor for the first 30–60 minutes post-migration:
   • CPU usage:    Compare against pre-migration baseline
   • Memory usage: Confirm consistent with source
   • Disk IOPS and throughput: Should meet or exceed source
   • Network throughput: Verify expected traffic patterns

3. If the migrated VM shows significantly higher CPU or I/O wait than before:
   • Check if Nutanix storage tiering (SSD/HDD) is optimised — initial data may be on HDD tier.
   • Run: ncli container ls  to confirm compression/dedup is not over-consuming resources.
   • Nutanix ILM (Intelligent Lifecycle Management) will auto-tier data to SSD within minutes.

4. For database VMs — run representative workload queries and measure response time.
   Compare against pre-migration query execution plans and latency.

5. Document the performance baseline readings for post-migration reporting.

5.3 Monitoring & Alerting Integration

STEP
14	Re-enable Monitoring and Update CMDB
	1. Re-enable / lift suppression of monitoring alerts for the migrated VMs.
   Update the VM identifiers (IP, MAC, hostname if changed) in your monitoring tool.

2. Verify monitoring agents are running on the migrated VMs:
   (e.g., Zabbix Agent, Prometheus Node Exporter, Datadog Agent, SNMP):
   Linux: systemctl status zabbix-agent / datadog-agent / node_exporter
   Windows: services.msc → verify monitoring agent service running

3. Confirm the VM appears in the monitoring dashboard and metrics are flowing.

4. Update the CMDB (Configuration Management Database) for each migrated VM:
   • Update: Hypervisor type (VMware → Nutanix AHV)
   • Update: Host/Cluster (ESXi cluster → NC2 cluster name)
   • Update: IP address, MAC address (if changed)
   • Update: Datastore / Storage (vSAN / VMFS → Nutanix storage container)
   • Update: Cloud provider / region (if NC2 is on AWS / Azure)

5. Update any load balancer configurations to use the new IP if it changed.
6. Update firewall rules / security groups to reference the new IP if it changed.
7. Verify backup jobs are re-enabled and pointing to the NC2 VM:
   • Nutanix Mine integration (if used)
   • Veeam Backup for Nutanix AHV (if used)
   • Or vendor-specific NC2 backup solution
   • Run a test backup to confirm the backup job completes successfully.


 
