7. Source VM Decommissioning

⚠️  Hold Period:  Do NOT delete source VMs immediately after migration. Maintain source VMs in powered-off state for a minimum hold period (recommended: 14–30 days) before decommissioning. This provides a safety net for rollback.

STEP
15	Source VM Retention and Decommissioning Procedure
	IMMEDIATELY AFTER SUCCESSFUL MIGRATION:
1. Confirm source VM is powered OFF on vCenter (do not restart).
2. Add a note/annotation to the source VM in vCenter:
   'Migrated to NC2 on <date>. Retain until <date + 30 days>. DO NOT DELETE.'
3. Remove the source VM from any monitoring groups (to avoid false alerts).
4. Remove the source VM from load balancer pool / DNS (if not already done).

DURING HOLD PERIOD (Days 1–30):
5. Monitor the migrated VM on NC2 for stability — watch for any issues requiring rollback.
6. If rollback is needed within the hold period: power on source VM in vCenter (< 5 mins).

AFTER HOLD PERIOD (Day 30+):
7. Obtain written approval from Application Owner to decommission source VM.
8. Take a final snapshot/backup of the source VM for archive purposes.
9. In vCenter: Right-click VM → Delete from Disk (or retain snapshot and remove from inventory).
10. Remove any associated resources:
    • vCenter alarms / DRS rules referencing the VM
    • Source VM backup jobs (cancel/delete in backup tool)
    • DNS / DHCP reservations for the old IP (if no longer needed)
11. Reclaim the released vCenter compute and storage capacity.
12. Update CMDB to mark the source VM record as 'Decommissioned'.


 
